title: For Sale/Trade:  BTJ DA 38 Special O/U Derringer Stainless Double Barrel
postcontent:
BTJ DA 38 marks, Stainless with aluminum frame. Tight with walnut grips in excellent condition..For Sell only to Tn resident legally able to purchase a firearm

 BTJ Stand for Bellmore Johnson Tool Co. Itt is my understanding that American Derringer picked up the rights to make this derringer and is in Blue Book under DA 38 Special...I found the following info on this derringer below which appears to be accurate..It was under a Gun Brokers blog.
 The original DA 38 Derringer was made only in 38 special chambering.
 The logo "BTJ" stands for Bellmore Johnson Tool Co. (the "T" is in the middle as a stylized logo)



 The DA frame is aluminum and the barrels and latch are stainless steel. The stainless castings were made by Pinetree Castings, the same company that Ruger often used.
 The original BJT derringers did not actually have wood grips but are made from a composite wood look-alike. 
 Later, the rights to manufacture and leftover parts were bought up by American Derringer Corporation, who began making these in 38 Special and 9 mm para. The earlier ADC-DA derringers have the BTJ logo and the Hamden CT address since they were leftover and already stamped by BJT. 
 The ADC derringers now have wood laminate grips.



 There is a difference between the ADC derringers and BJT that you can see at a glance: the Safety on the ADC derringers have a center screw to adjust the safety tension. The BJT derringers have a solid safety piece and do not have or need the screw.

title: For Sale:  Antique Rosewood Gambling Case with 1849 Colt Pocket
postcontent: The box is made out of rosewood or mahogany and my guess is that it is mid to late 1800s.  It is in good shape except a small season crack across the top above the inlay.  The first layer has a small antique roulette wheel with ivory spinner.  It does spin.  It has blue, red and ivory color clay chips, 4 antique glass jars, a bone or ivory turned dice cup, a bone or ivory round box with bone dice (season crack), a Elgin pocket watch (I wound it last night, it ran for a few hours and kept time).  An old deck of cards (not complete) with a very interesting tin or pewter card holder .  Under the tray is a Colt Pocket Serial #89097 (matching numbers).  The gun cocks and cylinder turns, but not every time - seems to do better if the barrel is pointing down.   Barrel is a little loose but overall a good gun.  It also has a powder flask which has an eagle on both sides, a wooden screwdriver and a brass colt bullet mold and a colt percussion tin box.  There is a brass pin on the right side of the box.  If you pull up on that pin, the bottom hidden drawer opens up revealing a bone handle straight razor, antique eyeglasses, 2 card cheat tools, poker dice, and a post card of guys playing cards.  This is really a cool set
